<TEXT>
the widow and children of a greyhound bus 
driver who was killed on a picket line have filed a 50 million 
lawsuit against the company and the replacement driver of the bus 
that crushed him 
robert waterhouse 59 was killed march 3 on the second day of a 
nationwide strike against greyhound lines inc he was crushed 
against a wall by the bus 
there have been numerous violent incidents since including 
several cases in which gunshots were fired at buses 
federal mediators have tried unsuccessfully to restart talks in 
the pay dispute between greyhound and the amalgamated council of 
local greyhound unions which represents the 6300 drivers and 
3000 other greyhound workers 
police are still investigating waterhouses death and the 
shasta county district attorney is expected to decide next week 
whether to file criminal charges 
the wrongful death suit filed in shasta county superior court 
names greyhound and the replacement driver hired for the strike 
theodore graham jr of portland ore 
the complaint alleges that greyhound was negligent in hiring 
graham in that graham was not qualified in training and 
disposition to drive a passenger bus 
the suit also alleges that the company employed nonunion drivers 
in an illegal attempt at strikebreaking and unionbreaking 
waterhouse was only months away from retirement after 32 years 
with greyhound 
</TEXT>
