<DOCNO> AP900325-0003 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the first rotary club in the soviet union has 
been officially established after several years of 
behindthescenes efforts the president of the international 
service organization said sunday 
a tired but happy hugh archer president of rotary 
international said three years of contacts between soviet 
ambassadors and rotary officials from around the world led to his 
final journey this weekend through the soviet bureaucracy 
it was difficult from the standpoint of intrigue in getting 
the word to the person who could help us archer said in a 
telephone interview sunday night after returning from to moscow 
nobody there wishes to speak as an individual what we had to 
do was get a lot of people convinced that it was ok to have a 
rotary club started in moscow 
archer finally got approval from soviet officials for a 
provisional club that will initially be made up of about 25 
business and professional people from moscow 
rotary international which has over 1 million members in more 
than 100 countries has forged growing links with eastern europe in 
recent years in june 1989 rotary established its first clubs in 
poland and hungary since world war ii said john obrien a 
spokesman for rotary international based in suburban evanston ill 
archer first met with soviet officials in december to explore 
the possibilities of opening a club in moscow he also visited a 
group eager to form a club in tallinn the capital of the soviet 
republic of estonia 
in a key discussion saturday with deputy minister of foreign 
affairs vladimir petrovsky archer said he received assurances the 
club can meet and select members without surveillance or 
restrictions and that it will be allowed to maintain contacts with 
clubs in other countries and contribute financially to the 
association 
rotarys constitution prohibits it from becoming part of another 
organization or being restricted by government or political forces 
it all follows from soviet president mikhail gorbachev 
because of his reforms that sort of paved the way obrien said 
but rotary has not gone cap in hand begging to open a club 
the members of the provisional club in moscow who have been 
holding informal meetings for the past six months range in age 
from 30 to 50 they include two lawyers three businessmen a 
theater manager and the head of a translation service 
archer said the group was delighted when told of the agreement 
and immediately began discussing ideas especially exchange 
programs with other countries involving rotary members as well as 
high school and college students 
he said the soviets at first had trouble understanding that they 
were expected to help people without receiving anything in return 
the concept of service as practiced by rotary and other groups 
is that you enjoy it without expectation of compensation archer 
said i think they got that idea 
rotary founded in chicago in 1905 is a notforprofit service 
organization consisting of business and professional men and women 
it sponsors educational and charitable programs and has a budget of 
56 million for 198990 
</TEXT>
