<DOCNO> AP900325-0006 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
hungarians voted sunday in their first 
free elections since 1947 and seemed determined to oust the 
communists who initiated democratic reform in hopes of gaining 
credit at the ballot box 
polling stations opened at 6 am with the last scheduled to 
close 14 hours later about 78 million hungarians are eligible to 
vote 
hungarians will choose a 394seat parliament in eastern europes 
second free elections a week after east germans backed a 
centerright movement to lead them to unity with west germany 
in a soviet bloc rushing toward democracy hungary remains 
unique while the people forced the communists in east germany 
czechoslovakia and romania to grant demands for democracy 
hungarys communists initiated reform then changed their name to 
the socialists and said they espoused westernstyle social 
democratic ideals 
yet there is little sign voters will reward them opinion polls 
suggest the socialists will end up with only about 10 percent of 
the overall vote 
in a year of remarkable reforms begun in the fall of 1988 
hungarys communists pointed the way for eastern europe by 
scrapping their partys guaranteed leading role from the 
constitution legalizing a multiparty system passing a new 
electoral law and altering the countrys name and emblem to wipe 
out communist affiliations hungary also opened its western border 
allowing thousands of east germans to flee their homeland and 
helping to bring about the fall of east germanys hardline 
communist leaders 
but those changes were overshadowed by memories of 43 years of 
communist rule in hungary 
in 1947 elections the communists won a relative majority 
largely through fraud a year later they consolidated power and 
forced all other parties out of existence 
all opposition parties contesting sundays ballot declared 
themselves open to almost any coalition scenario but excluded 
governing with the socialists 
a popular poster from the hungarian democratic forum one of the 
leading contenders for power symbolized the anticommunist 
antisoviet slant of the campaign it showed a bullnecked soldier 
with the russianlanguage caption comrades its all over 
while united in opposition to communism hungarians are unlikely 
to show a firm preference for any one party this would require a 
second round of voting tentatively scheduled april 8 
opinion polls suggested up to 25 percent of the voters were 
undecided about whom to back sunday 
international groups sent delegations to monitor the elections 
former vice president walter mondale leading a 50member group 
said there were a couple of pimples here and there in the 
campaign but no major problems 
the campaign centered mostly on unpleasant economic truths that 
are taking the edge off the thrill of choosing a government 
most parties agree that the stultified centralized economy 
should be converted to one governed by market forces none can deny 
the transformation is likely to bring unemployment and still higher 
prices to a country battling doubledigit inflation 
the new government also will inherit a 20 billion foreign debt 
the highest per capita in eastern europe 
another primary issue was romanias treatment of its ethnic 
hungarians at least seven people were killed last week in ethnic 
unrest in transylvania uniting all hungarian parties and awakening 
fears of neighboring romania 
at one opposition rally friday a woman expressed concern over 
any opposition move to accelerate the total withdrawal of soviet 
troops saying she feared a possible romanian military threat 
twelve parties garnered enough support to run on the national 
list in the complex electoral system forged by the communists and 
opposition last year 
seventeen other parties are running candidates on the local 
level with as many as 14 candidates in some races twentyone 
parties offered no candidates 
the six considered most likely to win seats in parliament are 
the hungarian democratic forum the league of free democrats the 
independent smallholders party the governing socialist party the 
league of young democrats and the social democratic party of 
hungary 
despite the broad palette of parties there were only two basic 
ideological trends on the political landscape the populist 
nationalism of the center right and more radical leftofcenter 
liberalism 
the conservative democratic forum lays considerable emphasis on 
hungarian traditions and christian values which are also espoused 
by the smaller hungarian peoples party and the christian 
democratic peoples party their strength lies largely in 
provincial towns outside budapest 
the forum led slightly in the most recent gallup poll from march 
12 with 21 percent 
next strongest with 203 percent were the free democrats a 
liberal party with social democratic leanings that wants to move 
hungary quickly toward a westernstyle society there was no margin 
of error cited in the poll 
third in the poll with 157 percent of support of the 1000 
respondents were the independent smallholders their main support 
is in rural hungary where they have pledged to return land taken 
by the communists to its owners 
the league of young democrats espouses views close to those of 
the free democrats and hopes to garner 10 percent of the vote 
</TEXT>
