<TEXT>
prime minister bob hawke said sunday it 
appeared his labor party prevailed in parliamentary elections and 
his conservative opponent andrew peacock conceded a labor victory 
was likely 
hawke speaking a day after saturdays vote said he expected a 
oneseat majority in the 148seat house of representatives he said 
a worst case scenario would give labor 73 seats and the 
conservative coalition 73 with two independents 
hawke clearly surprised by the apparent tight outcome said 
that when final results are in i hope it may be a bit better 
than that one seat it will give a sense of discipline for sure 
and we can do it 
peacock 51 would not concede defeat but on sunday the leader 
of the liberal and national party coalition acknowledged labor had 
a better chance of taking the election 
if you are setting a book i suggest the shortest odds would be 
regrettably on a hung parliament followed then by a labor 
government just ahead of a possibility of a coalition government 
peacock said in melbourne 
peacock who made his second bid for the prime ministership 
emphasized however the outcome of six or seven seats in the 
states of western australia and queensland still had not been 
decided 
vote counting routinely suspended for sunday was to resume 
monday political leaders said the results wont be known for sure 
until thursday when mailin ballots are counted 
forty of 70 senate seats were also contested saturday and early 
results showed the small democratic party made strong gains the 
house the more powerful chamber chooses the prime minister 
communities with undecided races included the small town of 
kennedy in northern queensland where several thousand voters were 
unable to cast their ballots because polling booths were cut off by 
floodwaters 
hawke 60 has governed for seven years he campaigned on his 
record of economic management despite dissatisfaction over record 
home mortgage interest rates and a 100 billion foreign debt 
hawke said the 1990 election would set the course for australian 
politics into the 21st century 
australia has 106 million eligible voters among its 165 
million people and voting is compulsory 
when vote counting closed saturday night labor appeared to have 
won 73 seats the coalition 70 and the independents two 
the independents the first elected in 24 years could hold the 
balance of power in the house labor which had 85 seats in the 
previous lower house needs 75 seats for a working majority 
australia is a close us ally and president bush said he hoped 
to visit the country before the years end 
hawke came to power in 1983 was reelected the following year 
and again in 1987 he has said that if reelected in this race he 
will seek a fifth term before retiring 
