<TEXT>
brazils new economic plan has led 
to the arrest of about 30 businessmen and bankers for economic 
crimes and a police raid on a company that publishes a book 
describing tax shelters 
several of the arrested businessmen have been held in jail for 
days without being charged and without a bail hearing some have 
been detained in cells containing people suspected of committing 
violent crimes 
the incidents critics say show that president fernando collor 
de mellos new economic measures have resulted in serious civil 
liberties violations 
we are heading for a dictatorship the arrests are a flagrant 
violation of rights consecrated in the constitution legal 
scholar gofredo de silva telles said in a television interview 
marcio tomaz bastos former president of the brazilian bar 
association told the associated press the new law is a 
violence if you kill someone you can respond to the charge at 
liberty but if you raise the price of a beer you can be jailed for 
months without trial 
collor announced his economic plan on march 16 one day after 
taking office as brazils first popularly elected president in 29 
years 
he passed the package using provisional measures which 
became law immediately but can be voted down by congress within 30 
days 
brazils supreme court is due to hear arguments on wednesday 
regarding the legality of the economic crime portion of the 
plan 
the measures designed to bring down record inflation that 
reached 2700 percent in the past year include a 30day price 
freeze a new national currency and a freeze on assets of more 
than the equivalent of 1200 from private savings accounts and 
600 from shortterm money market deposits 
the freeze withdrew an estimated 115 billion from circulation 
about 80 percent af all bank deposits 
also included was a controversial provisional measure that 
subjects managers and owners of companies that commit crimes 
against the popular economy to twotofouryear jail terms the 
law does not provide suspects with the right to apply for bail 
between the time they are arrested and tried 
in the 10 days since the plan was passed at least 30 
businessmen and bankers have been arrested and charged with 
violating the new law according to newspaper and television 
reports 
last week antonio gaspar manager of an eldorado supermarket 
was arrested in sao paulo brazils biggest city and charged with 
economic abuses the most serious being increasing the price of 
some fish by 500 percent 
on friday four members of the prominent verissimo family which 
owns the eldorado chain were arrested in connection with the case 
those charged were placed under house arrest and presumably will be 
tried later 
several bank managers in major cities have also been arrested 
and jeered by crowds as they were led away by police the managers 
were charged with denying clients the right to withdraw up to the 
legal maximum from their bank accounts 
public opinion polls show the economic plan has overwhelming 
public support one survey by the brazilian institute of public 
opinion and statistics the nations leading polling outfit found 
that 94 percent of the people supported jail time for economic 
crimes the company interviewed 2250 people in brazils eight 
largest cities no margin of error was provided 
several of the arrested businessmen have been held in jail for 
days some in cells containing people charged with violent crimes 
others accused of committing economic crimes have been freed on 
their own recognizance 
police raided the tama publishing house in rio on march 19 
seized copies of the book tax havens which describes various 
tax shelters and charged two of the companys officials with 
inciting tax evasion 
brazils 1988 constitution prohibits all censorship 
four days later the offices of folha da manha which publishes 
the prominent folha de sao paulo newspaper were raided by heavily 
armed federal police agents who arrested two company officers for 
