only six other states are supporting 
minnesotas contention before the supreme court that control of 
national guard training missions is a states rights issue 
the justices are scheduled to hear oral arguments tuesday on a 
suit by minnesota gov rudy perpich challenging the 
constitutionality of a 1986 law enacted in reaction to opposition 
from some democratic governors to former president ronald reagans 
central american policies 
perpich contends the montgomery amendment named after rep gv 
sonny montgomery dmiss violates the militia clause of the 
constitution because it denies governors authority to control the 
peacetime training of national guard units 
the amendment specifically bars governors from withholding 
consent to a national guard unit serving on active duty outside the 
country because they dont like the location purpose or schedule 
of the mission 
it was enacted after several governors said they opposed the 
reagan administrations policies in central america and did not 
want national guard units from their states assigned to train in 
the region 
officials from 29 states including 19 governors have filed 
briefs with the court supporting the montgomery law the supreme 
court last year rejected hearing a similar challenge to it by 
massachusetts officials 
perpich a democrat has not viewed the question as a foreign 
policy matter but as one of states rights 
the montgomery amendment is an unnecessary federal power grab 
that violates an unambiguous command in the text of the united 
states constitution minnesota officials said in their brief to 
the court 
the plain meaning of the militia training clause cannot be 
more evident the authority of training the national guard is 
reserved to the states 
massachusetts and five other states iowa maine montana ohio 
and vermont have filed a brief supporting minnesotas contention 
represented by their attorneys general the states wrote the 
supreme court that the founding fathers intended for states to 
control the militia to prevent abuses by the federal government 
there is no doubt that state control over the militia was an 
integral part of the framers planned structure as a means of 
securing the blessings of liberty won in the war of independence 
according to those states 
however the governors of 19 states and attorneys general for 10 
more states contend in their own brief filed with the supreme court 
