<TEXT>
the dead sea scrolls which include some of the 
earliest known biblical texts will be subjected to carbon14 
dating to discover whether they were written by a jewish group or 
early christians officials said sunday 
magen broshi custodian of the israel museums shrine of the 
book where some of the scrolls are on public display said at 
least 12 of the 799 scrolls will be dated using new carbon14 
techniques 
the dating would help settle arguments and conflicting theories 
about whether the scrolls were the product of a jewish group known 
as the essenes or a much later group of early christians said orna 
hess a spokeswoman for the antiquities authority 
most biblical scholars believe the scrolls date to the second 
century bc or late third century bc based on paleography or 
analysis of handwriting styles broshi said 
we relied on paleography we will now see if this method 
agrees with physics broshi said i dont believe there is any 
urgent need but this will keep people happy 
broshi said the testing would quiet critics like robert 
eisenman head of religious studies at california state university 
at long beach who do not accept the nonscientific dating 
in a telephone interview eisenman demanded that objective 
observers be allowed to witness the dating process and that more 
than one laboratory carry out the tests 
he said this was necessary because the scrolls are controlled by 
a team of scholars who have a vested interest in preserving their 
theories which are based on the established chronology 
in order to have a fair process one that would not be open to 
future questions people of differing shades of opinion should be 
brought into the process as observers eisenman said 
eisenman has backed the controversial theory that the 
unpublished scrolls may be the work of early christians his 
argument is based on the wording of the texts such as the use of 
certain phrases known to have been common among early christians 
and indirect references to the rule of king herod the great 
traditionally the scrolls are viewed as the work of a small 
mysterious sect known as the essenes scholars of this traditional 
school say they provide an insight into the life and religious 
thought of the ancient sect of jews as well as the roots of 
christianity 
ms hess said a small fragment had already been dated at 
israels weizmann institute of science she declined to discuss the 
results or give details as to how large a fragment was tested 
broshi said negotiations were under way with a european 
university with more advanced techniques to do the main body of 
work which was expected to start within the next few weeks 
neither broshi nor hess would say which university was involved 
none of the papyrus scrolls have been previously carbon dated 
because until a few years ago too much material had to be destroyed 
in the process broshi said 
the linen wrapping in which some scrolls were found was dated 
more than 30 years ago using primitive techniques it dated the 
cloth to 33 ad plus or minus 200 years 
scientists can date organic material on the basis of the amount 
of radioactive carbon14 remaining 
the new carbon14 technique called accelerator mass 
spectrometry requires only a small about of parchment for testing 
it was first employed to date a 27000yearold wooly mammouth 
found in siberia in 1977 
the first scrolls were found in caves at qumran overlooking the 
dead sea in 1947 and others were excavated over a 10year span 
from 11 caves some scrolls represent the earliest existing copies 
of books of the bible others contain poetry stories and legal 
texts 
</TEXT>
