<TEXT>
two strategies that boost the immune 
system to battle the most dangerous form of skin cancer show 
promise in early tests with patients a researcher said sunday 
twentythree percent of patients showed evidence of some 
remission of melanoma after injections in one of the experimental 
treatments primed their bodies to attack certain proteins found on 
melanoma cells said malcolm mitchell 
the injections are called theraccines short for therapeutic 
vaccines because they seek to treat cancer rather than prevent 
disease he said 
mitchell a professor of medicine and microbiology at the 
university of southern california school of medicine in los 
angeles described the work at a science writers seminar sponsored 
by the american cancer society 
about 27600 new cases of melanoma are expected this year with 
6300 deaths the society says intense exposure to the sun is a 
chief cause 
mitchells experimental injections make the immune system seek 
out proteins called antigens on cancerous cells the preparations 
are made from melanoma cells grown in the laboratory 
injections were done under the skin once a week for four weeks 
with a final injection on week six patients who responded were 
treated with a single monthly booster and semiannual courses of 
five more doses 
in 79 melanoma patients the treatment produced a complete 
remission in 5 percent and a partial remission in 18 percent 
mitchell said another 10 percent showed minor responses defined 
as tumor shrinkage of 26 percent to 50 percent 
no major side effects were observed he said 
other researchers have reported similar work clearly this is 
an attraactive approach said john laszlo the cancer societys 
senior vice president for research 
mitchell also reported on results from treating melanoma 
patients with low doses of interleukin2 a natural substance used 
by the immune system and a standard cancer drug called 
cyclophosphamide both drugs were given at about onethird the dose 
used in experiments or therapy 
in 39 patients the combination produced a 28 percent response 
rate including two complete remissions and eight partial 
remissions mitchell said 
potentially this treatment could be done by any hospital and 
its results are comparable to a more complex treatment in which 
interleukin2 is combined outside the body with white blood cells 
and then reinjected into the patient mitchell said 
in what he called the down note of his talk mitchell said 
some other forms of therapy will have to be found to deal with the 
spread of melanoma cells to the brain where they can form new 
cancers 
in a separate presentation a researcher said a study of 200 
people with or without melanoma suggests that six factors define 
people at high risk for getting the disease 
they are blond or red hair marked freckling of the upper back 
the presence of rough red bumps called actinic keratoses caused by 
to sun exposure a history of melanoma in other family members 
having had three or more blistering sunburns during ones teenage 
years and having spent three or more years at an outdoor summer 
job as a teenager 
having any one or two of these factors gives a person a three to 
four times increased chance of developing melanoma said darrell 
rigel of the new york university school of medicine 
people with three or more of the factors run an increased risk 
of 20 to 25 times he said 
people at high risk should be taught the ways to detect melanoma 
early when it is at a highly curable stage he said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

