workers at 11 hawaii hotels achieved a goal of 
parity with mainland workers under a tentative agreement ending a 
monthlong strike that left some hotel guests making their own 
beds labor leaders said 
the deal between local 5 of the hotel employees and restaurant 
employees and the council of hawaii hotels would give workers an 
average pay increase of 10 percent a year 
the strike affected about onefourth of the 37000 hotel rooms 
in waikiki the states tourist capital and about oneseventh of 
the states total number of hotel rooms 
as is the case with all contracts we didnt get everything we 
want but we did satisfy our needs union leader tony rutledge 
said after the agreement was announced saturday 
nearly 80 percent of workers will be earning nearly as much 
money as hotel workers in san francisco by the time the contract 
expires in 1994 rutledge said meeting one of the unions main 
goals 
the walkout by 7500 maids bellhops clerks restaurant and bar 
workers and others left some hotel guests doing without room 
service and making their own beds as managers struggled to fill the 
gaps some of the affected hotels offered discounts of up to 20 
percent 
the tentative accord reached after an allnight bargaining 
session was announced by union and management representatives 
gov john waihee and federal mediator frank schoeppel 
this will give stability to the industry for the next five 
years said william crawford executive director of the 
management council and chief negotiator for the hotels 
the union achieved its main goal of bringing pay in line with 
that of mainland hotel workers union spokesman roderick rodriguez 
said 
union members were to meet sunday to discuss the settlement and 
procedures for ratification but members were told they didnt need 
to wait for formal ratification and could return to work as soon as 
their hotels called for them to come in 
under the agreement wages and benefits for nontipped workers 
will increase 7 percent this year and 6 percent each of the next 
four years tipped workers will get raises totaling 85 cents an 
hour over the life of the contract 
workers also will get an increase of 99 cents an hour in health 
and other benefits to bring the total to 229 an hour 
the union failed to win a 5 percent room surcharge or a 15 
percent food and beverage surcharge that would have been divided 
among workers two issues it had labeled critical for a settlement 
rutledge said the tentative agreement would add about 40 cents 
per hour across the board to the one approved at another hawaiian 
hotel the union had been seeking increases of about 10 percent a 
year for three years 
salaries under the old contract range from an average of 385 
an hour for bellhops to an average of 1104 an hour for cooks 
